Q1. What is WWW?<br>
The World Wide Web (WWW) is a system of interlinked hypertext documents that can be accessed via the Internet. It was invented by Tim Berners-Lee in 1989 and is now the primary means of accessing and sharing information on the Internet.
        <hr>
Q2. Explain the term Internet?<br>
The Internet is a global network of interconnected computers and servers that communicate with each other using standardized protocols (TCP/IP). It enables data to be transmitted between devices, allowing for communication, information sharing, and online services.
        <hr>
Q3. Differentiate between WWW and Internet?<br>
Think of the Internet as the infrastructure (highways) and the WWW as a service (traffic) that runs on that infrastructure. The Internet enables the WWW to function, but the WWW is just one of many services that use the Internet.
        <hr>
Q4. What is URL?<br>
A Uniform Resource Locator (URL) is a web address that specifies the location of a resource (webpage, image, file, etc.) on the Internet. It consists of a protocol (http/https), domain name, path, and optional query string and fragment identifier.
        <hr>
Q5. Write a short note on Operating System?<br>
An Operating System (OS) is software that manages computer hardware resources (CPU, memory, storage, input/output devices) and provides a platform for running applications. Common OS tasks include process scheduling, memory allocation, file systems, and security.
<hr>
Q6. What is HTML?<br>
Hypertext Markup Language (HTML) is a standard markup language used to create web pages. It defines the structure and layout of content on the web, including headings, paragraphs, images, links, forms, tables, and more.
        <hr>
Q7. Describe the three layers of the web?<br>
The three layers of the web are:

1. Infrastructure layer (Internet): The underlying network infrastructure that enables data transmission.
2. Service layer (WWW): The system of interlinked hypertext documents that make up the web.
3. Application layer (web applications and services): The software applications and services that run on the web, such as social media, email, and online banking.
        <hr>
Q8. Discuss two-sided tags and one-sided (empty) tags with examples?<br>

Two-sided tags have an opening and closing tag, surrounding content:
Example: &ltp&gtThis is a paragraph &lt/p&gt

One-sided (empty) tags do not have a closing tag:
Example: &lt img src="image.jpg" alt="An image" &gt

Two-sided tags wrap around content, while one-sided tags stand alone. Let me know if you'd like more information or clarification on any of these points!
