Q1. Write a short note on Document Type Declaration?<br>

The Document Type Declaration (DTD) is a statement that defines the document type and version of HTML used in a document.<br>
It is placed at the very beginning of an HTML document and is essential for ensuring that the document is rendered correctly by web browsers.<br>
The DTD typically includes the document type (HTML), the version number, and the character encoding used.
          <hr>
Q2. Explain the &lthtml>, &lthead>, and &ltbody> tags?<br>

- &lthtml> is the root element of an HTML document and contains all the other elements.<br>
- &lthead> is a child element of &lthtml> and contains metadata about the document, such as the title, character encoding, and links to external stylesheets or scripts.<br>
- &ltbody> is a child element of &lthtml> and contains the content of the HTML document.<br>
          <hr>
Q3. Write a 'Hello World' HTML program.<br>

&lt!DOCTYPE html><br>
