Q1. Heading Tags:<br>

- Heading tags (H1-H6) are used to define headings and subheadings in HTML documents.
- They provide structure, accessibility, and visual hierarchy to content.
- Best practices include using H1 for the main title, H2-H6 for subheadings, and following a logical order.
            <hr>
Q2. Types of Lists:<br>

- Ordered lists (&ltol>) are numbered lists with &ltli> elements.
- Unordered lists (&ltul>) are bulleted lists with &ltli> elements.
- Definition lists (&ltdl>) consist of &ltdt> (term) and &ltdd> (definition) elements.
  <hr>
Q3. Absolute vs. Relative Paths:<br>

- Absolute paths include the protocol, domain, and file path (e.g., &lta href="(link unavailable)">).
- Relative paths reference a file relative to the current directory (e.g., &lta href="about-us">).
- Relative paths are useful for linking to files within the same website.
  <hr>
Q4. Linking Telephone Numbers:<br>

- Use the &lta> tag with the tel: protocol to create a clickable phone number link (e.g., &lta href="tel:+1234567890">+1-234-567-890</a>).
- This allows users to click and call the number directly.
  <hr>
Q5. Displaying Data with Tables:<br>

- Tables consist of &lttable>, &lttr> (rows), and <td> (cells) elements.<br>
- Header cells (&ltth>) define column headers.<br>
- Data cells (&lttd>) contain the data.<br>
- Rowspan and colspan attributes merge cells.<br>
- Border and padding styles enhance table appearance.<br>
  <hr>
Q6. HTML Comments:<br>

- HTML comments start with &lt!-- and end with -->.<br
  
- Comments are ignored by browsers and not displayed to users.<br>
- Use comments to add notes or hide code.<br>
