Q1. What is semantic markup?<br>

Semantic markup is the use of HTML elements to provide meaning to the structure of a web page, rather than just presenting the content. <br>
It involves using elements that describe the content, making it easier for search engines, screen readers, and other tools to understand the page's structure and content.<br>
              <hr>
Q2. List out various semantic elements.<br>

Some common semantic elements include:<br>

- Header (&ltheader>)<br>
- Nav (&ltnav>)<br>
- Main (&ltmain>)<br>
- Section (&ltsection>)<br>
- Article (&ltarticle>)<br>
- Aside (&ltaside>)<br>
- Footer (&ltfooter>)<br>
- Address (&ltaddress>)<br>
- Figure (&ltfigure>)<br>
- Figcaption (&ltfigcaption>)<br>
              <hr>
Q3. Discuss how section, article, aside, and address tags should be used.<br>

- Section (&ltsection>): Use for a self-contained section of related content, such as a chapter or a group of related articles.<br>
- Article (&ltarticle>): Use for a self-contained piece of content, such as a blog post or a news article.<br>
- Aside (&ltaside>): Use for tangential content, such as a sidebar or a pull quote.<br>
- Address (&ltaddress>): Use for contact information, such as a physical address or an email address.<br>
              <hr>
Q4. Explain how audio and video elements work with example.<br>

The audio and video elements are used to embed audio and video content in a web page.<br>

Example:<br>

&ltAudio controls><br>
&ltsource src="audio.mp3" type="audio/mp3"><br>
Your browser does not support the audio element.<br>
&lt/audio><br>
<br>
&ltVideo controls><br>
&ltsource src="video.mp4" type="video/mp4"><br>
Your browser does not support the video element.<br>
&lt/video><br>
<br>
The controls attribute adds playback controls, such as play, pause, and volume. The source element specifies the source file and type. <br>
The text inside the audio/video element is a fallback message for browsers that do not support the element.<br><hr>
